    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1941-12-26T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1941-12-26T00:00:00-05:00" n="814"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d814">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">861.24/769½</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">Memorandum by the Assistant Chief of the Division of European
                        Affairs</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Henderson</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to Mr. <persName type="to">Wright
                            Thomas</persName> of the Division of Exports and Defense Aid</hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">[<placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>,] <date calendar="gregorian" when="1941-12-26">December 26,
                            1941</date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>Thank you very much for sending me a copy of the draft agreement<note n="42"
                        xml:id="d814fn42">Draft of a lend-lease agreement between the United States
                        and the Soviet Union, not attached to the memorandum.</note> which I am
                    holding for the time being. In regard to that section relative to the protection
                    of patent rights, we believe that a consideration which should be borne in mind
                    is that the Soviet Government has not hesitated in the past arbitrarily to copy
                    any patented machine or article imported into the Soviet Union without paying
                    any attention to the foreign patentee. There is no reason to believe that the
                    Soviet Government would not continue this practice in the future and would not
                    hesitate to export articles patented in the United States but manufactured in
                    the Soviet Union.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>L[<hi rend="smallcaps">oy</hi>] W. H[<hi rend="smallcaps"
                        >enderson</hi>]</signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
